      <TEXTAREA NAME="body" ROWS="15"
        COLS="50" WRAP="virtual">>Since we are the ones creating all 
>these undead all over the lands 
>(in theory, anyway) we should be 
>interested in bolstering them and making 
>them more plentiful.  In that 
>light, increased XP for killing undead 
>is not a good idea... 
>There are still remnants of this philosophy 
>around -- the Gnome necromancer guild 
>faction hit of decaying newbie skeletons 
>in Steamfont, for example.  A 
>cleric might very well get an 
>XP bonus (logically, but I have 
>no idea if they actually do) 
>for killing undead; we should take 
>a hit of the same magnitude. 
>(And magicians should take a hit 
>for killing elementals in the same 
>way.) 
>I wouldn't hold out hope that there 
>is any XP difference at all, 
>though.  That requires extra database 
>work, and it's brutally obvious that 
>the database design was done long 
>before the full needs of the 
>game were thought out. 
>It's amazing how different the game is 
>when you don't mess up your 
>factions needlessly.  The second time 
>I played a necromancer (both Gnomes) 
>I only killed skeletons, pumas, and 
>minotaurs in my level 7-12 range. 
> In other words, only things 
>that attacked me.  Plague rats, 
>ebon drakes, harpies, and clockworks all 
>left me alone, and I, they. 
> In-character, I had done nothing 
>to them, and they nothing to 
>me.  (I like to play 
>my character very intellectually stuck up, 
>sort of like a female Dr. 
>Doom, using this or that thing 
>to my own ends...)  Actually, 
>that they had done "nothing to 
>me" was not a moral justification 
>of reciprocity in this sense.  
>Rather, it was a precursor for 
>their remaining alive.  A necessary 
>condition, but not a sufficient one 
>always, since I did...liberate a few 
>from this thing called life, purely 
>out of curiosity. 
>God, what a scumbag my character is! 
>
</TEXTAREA>
     
